## Part B — Velocity, joint, and workspace limits

### 7. Enforce joint position and velocity limits in software

- Every joint must have configurable upper/lower position bounds and a maximum
  velocity limit. Load these from a YAML config, never hardcode them.
- The planner and the controller must both independently reject trajectories
  that violate joint limits (defense-in-depth, same principle as dry-run).
- Use `joint_limits_interface` or equivalent saturation layer so that even if
  the planner produces an out-of-range command, the controller clamps it.

### 8. Cap tool-center-point (TCP) speed

- Define a maximum Cartesian speed for the end effector (e.g. 250 mm/s for
  hand-guiding, higher only after explicit risk assessment per ISO/TS 15066).
- Validate planned Cartesian velocities before sending; abort if any segment
  exceeds the limit.
- During manual/teleoperation modes, enforce a lower speed cap than in
  autonomous mode.

### 9. Define and enforce workspace boundaries

- Maintain a set of safety planes or bounding volumes that the tool and elbow
  must stay within. Define these in config, not in code.
- Before executing any trajectory, verify every waypoint lies inside the
  allowed workspace. Reject the entire trajectory if any waypoint violates.
- Include a floor-clearance check: `z_wrist >= FINGERTIP_BELOW_WRIST +
  MIN_FLOOR_CLEARANCE` (see Part I — Gripper geometry for values).

